Dnia sobota, 3 stycznia 2015 20:37:35 grarpamp pisze:
> > On 03/01/15 10:18, Shawn K. Quinn wrote:
> >> To me, any true successor to TrueCrypt will be available under GPL=
v3
> >> (not sure I like the idea of someone forking a BSD/MIT licensed cl=
one
> >> and then not sharing the source, aka the "BSD/MIT Tuck And Run")
>=20
> This is a bogus argument. If you don't like that someone has copied i=
t,
> closed it, and gone off and done their own thing with it... make your=

> own copy and continue open development. BSD is about honoring
> freedom, not about ramming freedom down your throat under threat
> of suit. World of difference there. Make no mistake, the more freedom=

> a license gives YOU, the more free it is. What you do with the freedo=
ms
> you are given is up to you... if you choose to jerk people around, no=
 one
> will care, they'll just ignore and route around you.

The good old BSD vs. GPL, eh?

The problem with this simplified view is that there are a number of goo=
d=20
reasons for copyleft clauses, and many of them were verified during=20
Heartbleed, for instance.

Apparently Facebook used a modified OpenSSL version that was accidental=
ly not=20
vulnerable. Had OpenSSL been licensed under a copyleft license, maybe w=
e=20
wouldn't have Heartbleed at all.

Another reason is a bit broader. In the digital world selling *products=
*=20
(think: Windows licenses) simply does not work -- the basic operation h=
ere is=20
*copying*, trying to make copying hard is not really that smart, is it.=
 We all=20
know how well DRM schemes work, right?

The answer here is to move towards selling *services* -- something that=
 is not=20
easily copy-able. Services like support, deployment, etc. But I guess w=
e all=20
know that already, don't we?

So why exactly does anybody here feel the need to retain the right to c=
lose=20
their (or anybody else's, for that matter) software? That doesn't seem =
like=20
it's required for selling services based on a given software, moreover =
=2D-=20
getting it out on a strong copyleft license (like GPLv3 or AGPL) makes =
it=20
*harder* for large corporations to close that work and out-sell it, and=
 at the=20
same time makes it easier to get all the patches/fixes/etc other people=
 made=20
in particular software.

I see huge practical and economical benefits from using copyleft licens=
es, and=20
the only argument *against* them is -- as far as I can see -- the "MUH=20=

FREEDUMS" aka "I might want to close-off some of my (or somebody else's=
)=20
work".

I actually feel copyleft licenses give me *more* freedom: I am at least=
 sure=20
nobody can close-off any version of a given (including: mine) program f=
rom me.



I have no problem with people advocating BSD/MIT-style licenses as long=
 as we=20
can have a civil discussion about it.

This:
> BSD is about honoring freedom, not about ramming freedom down your th=
roat
> under threat of suit.=20

...is not exactly what I am talking about here.

=2D-=20
